##Help the children! More than 100 epileptic children in Hubei, about to go off the drug!

Micro Signal Damihexiaomi 2015

Rice and Xiaomi are the leading service platforms for children with autism spectrum in China, providing integrated services such as rehabilitation training, integrated education support, parent training, online courses and popular science consultation. At present, we have set up service organizations and many integrated kindergartens in Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Shenzhen and Zhengzhou, and will expand to more areas in the future.

Liu Xiaohong looked at the growing epidemic, son Cong Cong anti-epileptic drug is eating less and less, she had some panic.

Brainy, now 5, was diagnosed with epilepsy when he was 2. Now you have to take two drugs twice a day to control it. However, affected by the "closure of the village" , the drug can not be added, existing drugs can only last until February 12.

Epilepsy commonly known as "epilepsy" , clinical symptoms for patients with sudden loss of consciousness, foaming, muscle rigidity and so on. At present, drugs are the main means of treating and controlling epilepsy. If the patient in the period of medication if there is no reason to reduce drugs, drugs, easily lead to recurrence of epileptic symptoms. And many antiepileptic drugs belong to the treatment of neuropsychiatric drugs, relatively difficult to purchase.

On January 21, two days before the city closure in Wuhan, Liu Xiaohong and her family returned from Changsha to their hometown in Hanchuan, Hubei Province, to return to Long Tieng for the Lunar New Year. She had calculated the time of her return journey and prepared more than 20 days'worth of medicines for Congcong.

The anti-seizure meds that cong was taking

By this time, COVID-19 coverage was overwhelming, but it did not seem to have affected the town, 110 kilometers from Wuhan. "There were not many people wearing masks on the streets, and there were still a lot of people doing business, " Ms. Liu recalled.

Two days later, the situation became serious. "every family closed their doors to let visitors in, and checkpoints were set up at every intersection, and no one was allowed to enter or leave. " Liu Xiaohong and her family were trapped in the village.

After the closure of the village, Liu Xiaohong, who was unable to go outside, had asked her relatives to pick up the medicine at a hospital in Hanchuan, but the medicine congcong needed, "debajin sodium valproate oral solution" and "topiramate tablets" , were not available locally; Liu Xiaohong also entrusted Shanghai, Changsha and other places to mail the drugs, but due to the current express delivery policy in Hubei, the drugs can not come in.

On February 5, Liu Xiaohong had driven back to Changsha to get medicine, on the way to the entrance of the highway was persuaded to return. A few days later, she went to the Huilong government and public security department to coordinate, but the result was only to "see the nearest doctor" .

At this point, Liu Xiaohong said she did not know who else to find, she only knew that if the drug did not have, brainy epilepsy is likely to recur.

Liu Xiaohong received by the village committee and the township government seal of the application to go out

I have medicine at home, but I can't get it

The plight of Liu Xiaohong's mother and son is not unique to families of epileptic children in Hubei Province. Some parents because of the "closure of the village road" , even if there are drugs, also can not get children around.

On Jan. 12, Wang Chu, who lives in Huangzhou District, Huanggang City, Hubei Province, drove 100 kilometers back to the town of Quanghe in Luotian County with his wife and two children. Wang Chu's two-and-a-half-year-old daughter has epilepsy and needs to be treated daily with the anti-seizure drugs "Keppra" and "oxcarbazepine" to control her condition. Back in Quantico, Wang Chu had brought her daughter's vacation supplies.

On New Year's Eve, January 24, Wang Chu's village was declared "closed" . Wang Chu said the village had blocked the road directly with sand and trees, while other villages on the road back to Huangzhou had even cut it off.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A roadblock in Huang Chu's village

With his daughter's medicine running low, Wang Chu wanted to drive back to her Huangzhou District home to get the medicine, which she could take for six months. But the village director said, lift the "closure of the village" time to wait for notice, if you want to leave the village now, then go to clear the roadblock.

Now her daughter had four days'supply left, Huang contacted the community at her home in Huangzhou, unlocked the door of her home, and mailed the pills to Quanghe. But the current situation is special, express delivery do not know when to arrive, coupled with the village road closure, express delivery can not be delivered to the village, Wang Chu has decided to walk to town to pick up the express.

Li Hui, whose ancestral home is Xinyan town in Hanchuan, Hubei Province, is also facing the dilemma of not getting medicine. Li's 8-year-old son, Cheng Cheng, has been treated for epilepsy for 4 years and now needs to take two drugs a day to control his condition. Under the influence of Hubei Express policy and the "closure of the village" , Li Hui's drugs at her residence in Anhui could not be distributed to her hands.

More trouble is that the sincere still do ketogenic diet, usually the food is a good Guangdong nutritionist with express delivery. Now, not only are the drugs on hold, Dietitians are unable to deliver meals from Guangdong in time, and the sudden cessation of the drugs and the Ketogenic Diet threatens to undo years of treatment.

Note: The ketogenic Diet is a high-fat, low-carbohydrate, protein and other nutrient-appropriate Formula Diet. The therapy has been used for decades to treat intractable childhood epilepsy in the last century.

Seeing Cheng Cheng on February 13 will be off drugs, Li Hui is particularly worried, before the Cheng because of epilepsy influence often can not sleep well, resulting in poor mental state, "if Cheng Cheng seizures again, very worried that he can not continue to school. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
SEISEI's daily medication

More than 100 epilepsy family imminent solution?

According to Rice and millet know, and the above 3 families have a similar situation in the family, there are hundreds of children, including drug reduction, withdrawal, relapse of epilepsy. They face two main difficulties:

One is that you can't buy drugs.

Over the counter epilepsy drugs can be purchased at pharmacies, but only at large pharmacies at or above the city level; prescription drugs must be dispensed at hospitals, but at present Grade III, Class A hospital in Hubei Province only accepts patients with fever, other departments were closed; some imported drugs could not be distributed.

Second, the basic logistics can not be distributed.

Even if the parents entrusted people to buy the medicine, but the road closure + express stopped transport, the medicine can not be sent in.

Some enthusiasts have decided to help the children in Hubei Province. From February 6, Hua Ma, the mother of epileptic children in Shanghai, has been calling attention to the problem on Weibo in succession. After seeing Hua Ma's initiative, Medical Volunteers Min Lei, Dai Shenyi and Han Zhiyi also joined in.

At the same time, Hua Ma also set up a wechat group called "Hubei Baby, come on! " For families in need of medicine, and volunteers counted each family's specific drug needs and quantities.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Screenshots of some of the group chats

After a few days of running contacts, several volunteers contacted the common epilepsy drug companies and pharmacies. On February 9, the volunteers made an emergency contact to arrange for a batch of medicines to be delivered to parents via EMS the next day.

Due to the variety of epilepsy drugs, General Pharmacy stock is less, so the current drug stock is not enough, the following drugs still exist gaps: Nitrazepam, Clonazepam, Lobazam, Xibaoning, topiramate capsules, oxcarbazepine oral solution, cAPRAM oral solution, zonisamide, Levocarnitine, calcium folinate, etc. .

"Even with medicines, transportation and postal services are still difficult to get to the village level, " Hua told Rice and Xiaomi. Currently, medicines are only distributed at the city or county level. The town post basically goes to the county every three days or so to pick up a parcel, and if no one urges, it may remain in the county warehouse for a week or more.

In the meantime, they hope that the postal service and other related parties will improve their business processes so that parents can deliver the medicine more quickly.
